It was... quite the opportunity. 
This short interaction told him two things:
1. This woman was uncaring of her surroundings. She had so blatantly stumbled into his living space, and judging by her words, seemed to not know where she was. She was likely drunk or hungover, or something to that effect. God forbid she had been smoking weed...
2. She was quick to conspiracy, which logically meant she was untrusting of others. People such as this are prone to being swept over by public safety initiatives, regardless of their intent or reach. This was the gap he was here to fill, no... to invert. 

There was a third thing, however. Earlier in this thought process, he criticized her for being unaware of her location. And yet, where the hell was he? If he were to accuse her of being drunk, would it not be logical to assume that someone in the same situation would have had the same lead-in? No, this was quite absurd. Indeed, Viotto did not feel drunk at all. In fact, he felt incredibly well-rested. But following the progression of events, what other possibilities were there? Was he picked up by... by... oh God...
